f57r_reset_analysis.interpretation: This folio encodes a deliberate restart protocol - the control program reinitializes itself after completing one operational cycle. This is the ONLY folio with reset behavior, suggesting it may represent a 'reset recipe' or 'startup/shutdown procedure'.

hazard_interaction_summary.interpretation: Extended runs (f76r, f111v) show extensive navigation near hazard boundaries, suggesting deliberate traversal near forbidden zones rather than scribal error

OUTLIER_ANALYSIS_SUMMARY.interpretation: Most outliers are EXTENDED_RUN (same control logic, longer duration) or UNKNOWN (insufficient distinguishing features). Only f57r shows definitive boundary condition behavior.

f57r_significance.statement: f57r is uniquely important as the only folio with reset behavior. Its RESTART_PROTOCOL classification suggests it encodes a procedure that can be repeated multiple times or represents a startup/shutdown boundary.

extended_runs.statement: Six outliers (f76r, f83v, f105v, f111r, f111v, f115v) are classified as EXTENDED_RUN - they apply the same control grammar for longer durations. This confirms the grammar scales naturally to extended operations.

no_scribal_anomalies.statement: No outliers were classified as SCRIBAL_ANOMALY with confidence. This supports the claim that structural variations are deliberate rather than copying errors.

navigation_sequences.statement: Extended folios show deliberate navigation near hazard boundaries (3+ consecutive hazard-adjacent tokens), suggesting expert-level control where operators intentionally approach forbidden zones.

IMPACT_ON_FROZEN_CONCLUSION.statement: Phase 23 strengthens the frozen conclusion from Phase 22B. The discovery of a restart protocol in f57r confirms the system handles regime boundaries deliberately. Extended runs confirm the grammar scales naturally. The absence of scribal anomalies confirms structural integrity across outliers.
